ğŸ› ï¸ Step 1: Install Git in Jenkins Server
ğŸ”¹ Install Git on Linux
For Ubuntu/Debian:
-  sudo apt update
-  sudo apt install git -y
For RHEL/CentOS/Amazon Linux:
-  sudo yum install git -y
-  git --version


ğŸ› ï¸ Step 2: Install & Configure Git Plugin in Jenkins
1ï¸âƒ£ Go to Jenkins Dashboard â†’ Manage Jenkins â†’ Plugins
2ï¸âƒ£ Search for "Git Plugin" â†’ Install it
3ï¸âƒ£ Restart Jenkins after installation

âœ… Configure Git in Jenkins
1ï¸âƒ£ Go to Manage Jenkins â†’ Global Tool Configuration
2ï¸âƒ£ Scroll to Git and set:
Path to Git executable: /usr/bin/git
3ï¸âƒ£ Click Save

ğŸ› ï¸ Step 3: Generate SSH Key for Jenkins (If Using Private Repo)
If you're using a private GitHub repo, Jenkins needs SSH authentication.

1ï¸âƒ£ Generate SSH Key for Jenkins
-  sudo -u jenkins ssh-keygen
2ï¸âƒ£ Copy the Public Key
-sudo cat /var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.pub

3ï¸âƒ£ Add the Public Key to GitHub
Go to GitHub â†’ Settings â†’ SSH & GPG Keys â†’ New SSH Key
Paste the public key and save

âœ… Test SSH Connection
-  sudo -u jenkins ssh -T git@github.com
If successful, you should see:
Hi <your-github-username>! You've successfully authenticated.

ğŸ› ï¸ Step 4: Create a New Jenkins Job for GitHub Integration
1ï¸âƒ£ Go to Jenkins Dashboard â†’ New Item
2ï¸âƒ£ Enter a Job Name (e.g., GitHub-Integration-Job)
3ï¸âƒ£ Select Freestyle Project â†’ Click OK
4ï¸âƒ£ Under Source Code Management, select Git
5ï¸âƒ£ Add your GitHub Repository URL

For Public Repos: Use HTTPS (e.g., https://github.com/your-username/your-repo.git)
For Private Repos: Use SSH (e.g., git@github.com:your-username/your-repo.git)
6ï¸âƒ£ Under Build Triggers, select "Poll SCM" and set:
H/5 * * * *  # Polls GitHub every 5 minutes
7ï¸âƒ£ Under Build Steps, select "Execute Shell"
8ï¸âƒ£ Add the following script:
echo "Cloning Repository..."
git pull origin master
echo "Build completed successfully!"
9ï¸âƒ£ Click Save & Build Now

âœ… Hands-On Practice:
Run the job and check the Console Output
Verify Jenkins is pulling the latest code

ğŸ› ï¸ Step 5: Automate Builds with GitHub Webhook
Instead of polling every 5 minutes, we can trigger Jenkins automatically using GitHub Webhooks.

ğŸ”¹ 1ï¸âƒ£ Configure Webhook in GitHub
Go to your GitHub Repository â†’ Settings â†’ Webhooks
Click "Add Webhook"
In Payload URL, enter:
http://<your-jenkins-server-ip>:8080/github-webhook/
Select "application/json" as Content Type
Under Which events would you like to trigger this webhook?, select:
âœ… Just the push event
Click Add Webhook

ğŸ”¹ 2ï¸âƒ£ Enable Webhook Trigger in Jenkins
1ï¸âƒ£ Go to Jenkins â†’ Your Job â†’ Configure
2ï¸âƒ£ Under Build Triggers, select "GitHub hook trigger for GITScm polling"
3ï¸âƒ£ Click Save

âœ… Hands-On Practice:
Push a new commit to GitHub
Check if Jenkins automatically starts a new build

ğŸ› ï¸ Step 6: Verify Jenkins is Triggering Builds
1ï¸âƒ£ Check Build History
Go to Jenkins Dashboard â†’ Your Job (GitHub-Integration-Job)
Look at the Build History panel on the left
If a new build appears after your GitHub commit, the webhook worked âœ…
If no new build appears, the webhook did not trigger âŒ
2ï¸âƒ£ Check Console Output for the Latest Build
Click on the latest build in Build History
Click Console Output
Check for messages like:
Started by GitHub push
Building in workspace /var/lib/jenkins/workspace/GitHub-Integration-Job
Pulling latest code from GitHub...
If you see this, Jenkins was triggered by the GitHub webhook. ğŸš€



